article.description: Keith Van Horn is used to starting over. He made his first start with the Milwaukee Bucks a successful one.
article.headline: Van Horn ties season-high with 30 points
article.linkText: Van Horn starts, Bucks edge out Grizzlies
article.story:
MILWAUKEE (AP) -- It didn't take long for Keith Van Horn to fit in with the Milwaukee Bucks. Just five games after being traded from New York on Feb. 15, Van Horn made his first start and tied his season high with 30 points in the Bucks' 106-104 victory over the Memphis Grizzlies Friday night. Van Horn came off the bench in his first four games, but he replaced Joe Smith (sprained left ankle) in the starting lineup Friday. "Like I said when I got here, I felt that this team had a lot of guys that play together very well, that understood the game, that played unselfishly," Van Horn said. "It's made it a lot easier for me to fit in." Nothing about the win was easy for the Bucks, though, who avenged their worst loss of the season, a 105-85 defeat on Feb. 6 in Memphis. There were 16 ties and 18 lead changes before Michael Redd's free throw with 22 seconds left gave the Bucks a 105-104 lead. His second shot hit the front of the rim and Shane Battier grabbed the rebound. With 5.3 seconds left, Battier caught an inbounds pass from Jason Williams and had a good look at the basket, but he missed the shot from the top of the key. "I took a couple dribbles to the middle and let it fly," Battier said. "I hit a couple this year, but it didn't go down for me tonight." Desmond Mason was fouled with seven-tenths of a second remaining and made one of two free throws for the final margin. Redd scored 19 points on 6-of-16 shooting. Desmond Mason and Brian Skinner each added 17. James Posey led Memphis with 25 points and 10 rebounds, and Bonzi Wells scored 19. The Grizzlies lost for the first time all year when shooting better than 50 percent and for just the second time when topping 100 points. They outshot the Bucks 53 percent to 45 percent and outrebounded them 41-32. But Milwaukee outscored Memphis 25-13 from the free throw line. The Bucks missed 16 out of 21 third-quarter shots, and the Grizzles turned a six-point halftime deficit into a 80-78 lead going into the fourth quarter. "They played well. They're very well coached. They made good plays," Redd said. "We won the game luckily."

Game notes
Smith is averaging 10.2 points and a team-high 8.6 rebounds. ... Van Horn made his first 17 free throws after being traded to the Bucks on Feb. 15. A lane violation negated his 18th, and he missed the retry. ... Official Rodney Mott participated in a league-wide protest of colleague Michael Henderson's suspension for an errant call. Mott turned his jersey inside out and wore Henderson's No. 62. Mott declined to comment about the protest after the game. Referees Eddie F. Rush and Nolan Fine did not take part in the protest.
